RESEARCH-HABITS
Evidence-based methods for successfully forming habits: how automatic
behaviour is built, what makes it stick, and what to do when it breaks.

Compiled 2026-07-24. Every claim below is tied to a numbered reference in the
REFERENCES section; numbers in brackets, e.g. [1], point there.


====================================================================
1. WHAT A HABIT ACTUALLY IS: THE CUE-BEHAVIOUR LINK
====================================================================

A habit is not "doing something a lot". It is a learned association between a
context cue and a response, so the cue alone triggers the behaviour with little
thought or motivation. This automaticity is the goal, not the frequency.

* Lally et al. (2010) [1] tracked 96 people adopting one new eating, drinking,
  or activity behaviour daily for 84 days, measuring automaticity each day.
  Automaticity rose along an asymptotic curve: fast at first, then flattening.
  Practical reading: a habit is "formed" when the action feels automatic, not
  when you have simply repeated it enough times.

* Wood & Runger (2016) [2] review the mechanism: habits are cued by recurring
  context (time, place, preceding action, mood), and once established they run
  independently of your current goals or intentions.
  Practical reading: build the behaviour onto a stable, recurring cue, or it
  will keep depending on motivation you cannot guarantee.


====================================================================
2. HOW LONG IT TAKES (AND WHY "21 DAYS" IS A MYTH)
====================================================================

There is no fixed number of days. The popular "21 days" figure has no basis in
the habit-formation literature.

* In Lally et al. (2010) [1] the median time to reach the automaticity plateau
  was 66 days, but the range across individuals and behaviours ran from 18 to
  254 days. Simpler behaviours (drinking water) automated faster than complex
  ones (doing sit-ups).
  Practical reading: expect roughly two months for something simple, longer for
  anything effortful. Judge progress by how automatic it feels, not the calendar.

* The same study found that missing a single opportunity did NOT measurably
  harm the automaticity curve [1].
  Practical reading: one slip does not reset your progress. Consistency matters
  in aggregate, not perfection day to day.


====================================================================
3. THE STRONGEST TOOL: IMPLEMENTATION INTENTIONS
====================================================================

Deciding IN ADVANCE exactly when, where, and how you will act - an "if-then"
plan - is one of the best-supported techniques for turning an intention into
action.

* Gollwitzer & Sheeran (2006) [3] meta-analysed 94 studies (over 8,000 people)
  and found implementation intentions had a medium-to-large effect (d = 0.65)
  on goal attainment, on top of merely intending to act.
  Practical reading: write "When situation X arises, I will do Y." e.g. "After
  I pour my morning coffee, I will read one page." The plan pre-links a cue to
  the response, which is exactly the structure of a habit (Section 1).

* They work by delegating control to the cue: the "if" part makes the situation
  highly accessible, and the "then" part makes the response automatic when the
  cue appears [3].


====================================================================
4. ANCHOR THE NEW BEHAVIOUR TO AN EXISTING ONE (STACKING)
====================================================================

A reliable cue is an existing routine. Attaching the new action to something
you already do every day borrows that routine's stability.

* Judah et al. (2013) [4] tested flossing: participants who planned to floss
  AFTER brushing (an existing habit) sustained the behaviour better at follow-up
  than those without such an anchor.
  Practical reading: pin the new habit to the end of an established one -
  "after I brush, I floss" - rather than to a vague time of day.

* This is the same cue-response logic as implementation intentions [3], with the
  "if" deliberately chosen to be an action you never skip.


====================================================================
5. MAKE IT EASY: FRICTION IS DECISIVE
====================================================================

Small changes to how much effort a behaviour takes have outsized effects,
because habits run on low deliberation and follow the path of least resistance.

* Rozin et al. (2011) [5] moved cafeteria food items a few inches or changed
  serving ease; convenience alone shifted consumption substantially without
  anyone deciding to eat differently.
  Practical reading: reduce the steps to start the good habit (lay out gym
  clothes the night before) and add steps to the bad one (unplug the TV,
  delete the app).

* This complements automaticity: when a behaviour is easy, the cue is enough to
  trigger it; when it is effortful, it stays dependent on scarce willpower [2].


====================================================================
6. REWARD AND REPETITION: WHAT REINFORCES THE LOOP
====================================================================

Repetition in a consistent context is the engine, but reward determines whether
repetition happens long enough for automaticity to take hold.

* Wood & Runger (2016) [2] note that rewards matter most EARLY, to drive the
  initial repetitions; once the habit is automatic, it persists even when the
  reward fades. Intrinsically enjoyable behaviours automate more readily.
  Practical reading: make the early reps rewarding (pick a form of the habit you
  like; add an immediate small reward), knowing you can drop the prop later.

* Immediate rewards beat delayed ones for habit formation, because the cue-
  response-reward loop must close quickly to be learned. Woolley & Fishbach
  (2017) [6] found that enjoyment of the activity itself predicted persistence
  better than its long-term value did.
  Practical reading: choose a version of the behaviour you find pleasant NOW,
  not just one that is good for you later.


====================================================================
7. IDENTITY AND SELF-CONCEPT
====================================================================

Behaviours tied to how you see yourself are more durable than those pursued as
isolated tasks.

* Gardner & Lally (2018) [7] and related work argue that habits which align with
  a valued identity ("I am a runner") receive ongoing support from that self-
  concept, reducing reliance on moment-to-moment motivation.
  Practical reading: frame the habit as evidence of who you are becoming, and
  let small consistent actions accumulate into that identity.


====================================================================
8. WHEN HABITS BREAK - AND HOW TO USE THAT
====================================================================

Because habits are cue-driven, changing the cues (context) both threatens old
habits and opens a window for new ones.

* Verplanken & Wood (2006) [8] describe "habit discontinuity": when context
  changes (a move, a new job, a new routine), existing habits lose their cues
  and behaviour becomes deliberate again.
  Practical reading: bad habits are easiest to drop during a life change, when
  their cues have already been disrupted. Deliberately remove or alter the cues
  of a habit you want to stop.

* The flip side: a disrupted context also makes it harder to KEEP good habits,
  so after a move or schedule change, re-establish your cues on purpose rather
  than assuming the habit will survive on its own [8].


====================================================================
9. PLANNING FOR LAPSES
====================================================================

Setbacks are normal and, handled well, do not derail habit formation.

* As in Section 2, a single missed occasion did not reset the automaticity
  curve in Lally et al. (2010) [1]; only sustained gaps did.
* An "abstinence violation" mindset - treating one lapse as total failure - is
  itself a strong predictor of relapse (Marlatt & Donovan, 2005) [9].
  Practical reading: pre-plan a recovery rule ("if I miss a day, I resume the
  next day, no penalty") so one slip does not become a spiral.


====================================================================
10. A PROTOCOL THAT FOLLOWS FROM THE ABOVE
====================================================================

1.  Pick ONE small, specific behaviour, in a form you actually enjoy [1][6].
2.  Choose a stable, recurring cue - ideally an existing daily action to anchor
    onto [2][4].
3.  Write an if-then plan: "After/When [cue], I will [behaviour]" [3].
4.  Cut the friction to start it; add friction to the competing bad habit [5].
5.  Give the early repetitions an immediate reward; expect to drop it later [2][6].
6.  Repeat in the SAME context every available opportunity - consistency of cue
    matters more than intensity [1][2].
7.  Judge progress by how automatic it feels, not by day count; expect ~2 months
    or more [1].
8.  Pre-plan a lapse-recovery rule; resume next day without self-punishment [1][9].
9.  Frame it as part of who you are becoming [7].
10. After any big change of routine, deliberately rebuild your cues [8].


